{"key":"post-15317254","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>15317254</id>\n<content>As has been said repeatedly around here by everyone but rank noobs, spraying the sides of a terrarium is a waste of time and water.&amp;nbsp; It's the cakes themselves which need water, not the plastic which has no use for it whatsoever.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The mutations are normal, but those should have been picked days ago before the caps fully opened.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The small fruits are due to insufficient substrate moisture because you're spraying the walls instead of the cakes themselves.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Misting based on hygrometer reading is false reasoning.&amp;nbsp; You don't mist to raise humidity except as a secondary benefit.&amp;nbsp; The perlite is for creating humidity, and you mist the CAKES to replace moisture that has been lost due to giving proper fresh air exchange.&amp;nbsp; When you mist the cakes, the overspray lands on the perlite, re-moistening it so it continues to provide humidity, while the holes provide for proper fresh air exchange.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>15317299</next>\n<prev>15317238</prev>\n<first>15317238</first>\n<last>15317444</last>\n<when>1320340626</when>\n<utime>11/03/11 08:17 PM</utime>\n</post>"}